of feet of earth and rock from the surface, to waft gently across her flushed, sweat beaded brow. The rock beneath her was rough and cool, a welcome feeling against her hot skin through the newly battered tunic. A warm and sticky fluid trickled down her lips, across her cheek and to the floor, oozing from the wound inflicted by her own teeth, as she bit down to hold herself from crying out as that mercifully cool ground rushed up to meet her. <br>
<br>
&quot;Your getting better, whelp, but you're still pathetic. Stand, and we'll do another pass before I send you to actually earn your slops. Innoruuk knows, you're not a good enough Knight to feed yourself that way.&quot; The rough voice came from above her, and soon, her vision cleared enough to show her the grizzled face of Ulraz S'lon, her trainer-at-arms. The girl began to shove herself to her feet, careful not to use the dulled short sword she bore as a crutch. She'd tried that once, and had nearly been unable to stand again, as the trainer had kicked it from her, sending it bouncing across her neck as she fell again. Well, it was a lesson learned. <br>
<br>
Once she was standing again, she fell into the ready position, now almost familiar to her, after these long hours of training with the blade. Ulraz smiled slightly, and then simply lunged with his own blade, a shining, yet similairly blunted great sword. The girl managed to bring her blade up far enough, fast enough, to deflect the blade  so that it hurtled past her cheek, giving her the time she needed to slash almost wildly with her own blade, hard enough to ring against the other's chest plate. As the sound rang out, the man almost smiled again, as he brought his blade back to it's ready position. &quot;I hope I'm wrong about you, whelp. Now, begone to the hall of service, and do not forget the care of your blade.&quot;<br>
<br>
The girl bowed, then began to slip away as she sheathed her 'blade' in the rough sheath given to her for that purpose. As she strode through the Hall of the dead, one of the practicioners of the Sacred Art called to her.. &quot;Little sister, we require the shards of the undead, so that our students may practice the Art. Go, and bring as many as you can to us.&quot; The girl simply bowed in return, with a swift nod.. After all, it was not wise to irritate those who could reach beyond the veil of death. And so the girl stepped forth from the house of the dead, and strode past the reeking ghouls set to guard that dread mansion, her feet swiftly carrying her through the city to the tunnel to the overworld. <br>
<br>
Here then, the dim light filtered through the dismal clouds and the dead branches to leave a dappled pattern on her face, that same cool breeze as earlier now caressing more than just her face through the battered tunic. As she walked across the soft fungus undergrowth, a familiar reek drifted to her nose. Those risen through the Art, and close. The girl crested a hill then, and that which she smelled came into view. <br>
<br>
The skeleton was half rotted, and free of any Necromancer's control, and stood there, vacantly staring into the woods. The girl's training blade made a steely rasp as she drew it, the skeleton still ignorning her, its rusted axe held almost loosely in one hand. &quot;If it's bone chips they desire, it will be bone chips they recieve.&quot; And with that, she swung her blade as mightily as she could, being rewarded with the shattering of the things left arm.. And then the battle began in earnest, the swift knight in training hammering at the animated dead over and over, while it's bony hand tried to bring the dulled blade of the axe over to chop at her. It wasn't long before the ancient warrior drew his first blood in years, the thick red fluid drizzling down from the girl's wounded shoulder. As the skeleton cackled in mad glee, she brought her own blade down, in a massive, overhand blow. Weakened though it was, it still was more than suffiecient to shatter the creature's skull, in an explosion of shards of bone. <br>
<br>
Her quick hand begane to snatch up those shards, the girl manageing to gather up almost half of what it would take for a practitioner to summon up a true servant of his own. And then her hand closed about the fallen axe. Though heavy, and dull, the rusty blade would serve her far better than her training blade in a real fight. <br>
<br>
The new Shadow Knight known as Arathena then straightened herself into the breeze, wondering exactly what this venture into the world beyond Neriak would bring her. <p>--<br>
